title: For Sale:  Taurus PT99
postcontent:
The Taurus PT92 is a double action/single action, 9x19mm Parabellum, double-stack magazine, semi-automatic, short recoil action pistol manufactured by Taurus in the former Beretta factory in SÃ£o Paulo, Brazil.

A large contract for the Beretta 92 was with the Brazilian army, for which Beretta set up a factory in Brazil. This factory was later sold to the Brazilian gunmaker Taurus (Forjas Taurus S/A ). Taurus makes these pistols (called the PT92) without the need for a license from Beretta since their design is based on the original Beretta 92, whose patents have since expired.

Like the Beretta, the Taurus PT92 utilizes the open-slide design where the upper portion of the slide is cut away exposing much of the barrel itself. The original PT92 was exactly like the original Beretta 92, though it was also unusual for the time in that it featured a squared trigger guard for supporting the index finger of the opposite hand while firing, a feature which was subsequently introduced to the Beretta 92 with the 92SB-F (92F) model in 1985. The Taurus PT92 is less expensive than the Beretta 92 in most cases.

Other versions of the PT92 include the PT99, which has an adjustable rear sight and a taller front sight.

Clean PT99 with 2x14 round clips

Asking book value, no more/no less

title: For Sale/Trade:  46100E armor plates with certs
postcontent: I have one set left for $125.  MIL-A-46100E 1/4" steel plate is military spec steel for armor applications. It exhibits high-hardness that is approved for use within the Department of the Army and is available for use by all Departments and Agencies of the Department of Defense. The high hardness properties of MIL-A-46100E provide for excellent resistance to penetration. This steel was developed specifically for military ballistic threats in personnel carriers, tanks, buildings, and anything else that requires protection against high velocity projectiles. This steel far outperforms AR500, which was developed for abrasion resistance and was never meant for ballistics. There is a reason the military developed this steel to use to protect our troops.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Gen 3 Glock 22 Package!
location: St. Tammany Parish, New Orleans, Louisiana
postcontent:
Having recently bought a Gen 4 Glock 17, I really don't need my Glock 22 Gen 3, and feel someone else would enjoy its use. The pistol was formerly owned by an Orleans Parish Sheriff's Deputy until they converted to 9mm, when he then sold it to a pawn shop in Slidell. I bought it from that pawn shop and it was my very first pistol and Glock. I absolutely love it, and it has very minimal wear from use (ignore the photos, it is only glare from the light, refer to third photo for true coloring). It was primarily my truck gun and I used it to complete a concealed carry course. I personally have put about 300 rounds through it, not sure how much before that was fired. But I have always cleaned it after every range visit, and monthly general cleanings. Bore is in spectacular shape. The frame is solid, and the slide is good to go. Have had zero issues with this firearm.

Now, I have a lot of stuff to go with it. I am including the following:

- Original Glock case
- Slide lock
- Magazine load assist
- Two 10 round magazines
- Six 15 round magazines
- 450 rounds of .40 S&W ammo that varies from 180gr Winchester White Box, 165gr Winchester Target, 180gr Lawman, 180gr XTP Hornady (hollow points).

For the entire package I'm asking $700. Very firm. I am open to trades so long as they are fair. NO SHOTGUNS. I am open to milsurp (no Mosin Nagants).

If you'd like to buy or trade you must be a Louisiana resident willing to meet FTF and be 21 years or older. Also must present a valid LA ID and sign bill of sale at time of transaction. No exceptions.

All in all I don't think you'll find a better packaged deal for a solid firearm.

title: For Sale:  SOLD - 1910 Mauser C96  "Broomhandle"
postcontent:
SOLD - Mauser C96  "Broomhandle"
year of manufacture 1910. 7.63 Mauser cal., 5 1/2 in. barrel, 10 shot mag., 32 groove walnut grips,  50-1,000 meter adj. rear sight. Includes  Wood Holster Stock.  An Oyster Bay Industries 9 OBI extended magazine, magazine catch &  an upper reciever Post War 9mm "Bolo" Barrel are also included.  

This 1910 "Broomhandle" is all original and in great condition for a sidearm of this age, there are no major flaws or problems. Wear on this pistol is where it should be-on the sideplate, barrel, and grip strap due to holster wear and usage. The numbers on the inside of the grips match that on the barrel & the only other visible number next to the hammer.  The holster stock is either original or an original quality reproduction.  

The long magazine and magazine catch is a 9 OBI. Oyster Bay Industries was an American company that made a detachable magazine conversion kit for the Mauser. It removes the floor plate, spring and follower and added a small magazine catch mechanism that allows it to feed its own brand of proprietary 9mm magazine using the replacement 9mm upper reciever.  This Post War 9mm Bolo Barrel upper reciever has a 50-1,000 meter tangent sight.  Due to the terms of the Treaty of Versailles, German pistols were limited to 100 mm (3.9in.) barrels or shorter, and calibers under 9mm.  Mauser satisfied these restrictions by reviving an older variant, popularly known as the Bolo.  Note this  Bolo barrel may have been forgotten and neglected once set aside in the twentys.  There's some pitting on the barrel & next to the front sight of the Bolo and may have later been refinished & had some parts replaced. 

If interested please call or text to 505-three two one-4552. (Please leave a message)  Cash only please.   Can be shipped to an out of state FFL where legal (will accept Postal Money Orders or PayPal with guns held at the shipping FFL till funds are confirmed).
